Motivation_Other_Long: “Recurrent ingestion in context of borderline personality disorder and PTSD. Frequently denies suicidal intent; behavior appears habitual, emotionally driven, and occasionally covert. Ingestion paused during long-term inpatient stay, resumed post-discharge.”
Comments: “Dx: PTSD + BPD. History of self-injury and suicide attempts. Multiple episodes of ingestion and vaginal insertion of sharp objects. Denied intent in most cases, though suicidal ideation present at times. Ingestion began age 22, paused at 25 during long-term stay, resumed after discharge.”
Authors: Gitlin D.F.; Caplan J.P.; Rogers M.P.; Avni-Barron O.; Braun I.; Barsky A.J.
Title: Foreign-body ingestion in patients with personality disorders
Comments_Reasoning: Does not report outcomes or elaborate on physical condition.

Comments: "She often refused to have foreign objects removed from her gastrointestinal tract unless the physicians agreed to surgical intervention for her perineal pain."
Authors: Gitlin D.F.; Caplan J.P.; Rogers M.P.; Avni-Barron O.; Braun I.; Barsky A.J.
Title: Foreign-body ingestion in patients with personality disorders

Authors: Blaho, Kari E.; Merigian, Kevin S.; Winbery, Stephen L.; Park, Lynda J.; Cockrell, Mike
Title: Foreign Body Ingestions in the Emergency Department: Case Reports and Review of Treatment

Outcome_Other_Long:
"His main symptoms before death were abdominal
pain with distention and no bowel movement for 3 days.
He vomited undigested material before his death, and
this was attributed to intestinal obstruction and car-
diopulmonary arrest. Autopsy permission was not granted
by relatives."
Authors: Dumaguing, Noel I.; Singh, Indra; Sethi, Mohammad; Devanand, D. P.
Title: Pica in the geriatric mentally ill: unrelenting and potentially fatal
Publication_Title: Journal of Geriatric Psychiatry and Neurology
Comments_Reasoning: No autopsy to report cause of death or to prove ingestion of objects.
